	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Analysis of preference erosion and distortion to agricultural incentives</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 May 2009
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The World Bank has recently produced two books dealing respectively with preference erosion and distortions to agricultural incentives in Africa. The publication on preference erosion reviews the current value of preferential access, the implications of preference erosion under different scenarios and the possible policy responses to the challenges faced. There are three distinct sets of papers focussing on: the non-reciprocal preference schemes of individual countries; sectoral features of preference schemes (agricultural products, non-agricultural products, textiles and clothing); the overall effects of preference erosion and options for dealing with preference erosion resulting from non-discriminatory trade liberalisation.</p><p>Chapters of particular relevance to the ACP-EU agricultural trade relationship include: </p>
<ul>

<li>‘What are EU trade preferences worth for sub-Saharan Africa and other developing countries’; </li>

<li>‘Quantifying the value of preferences and potential erosion losses’; </li>

<li>‘Non-reciprocal preference erosion arising from MFN liberalisation in agriculture: what are the risks of’; </li>

<li>‘The Doha development agenda and preference erosion: modelling the impacts; </li>

<li>‘Economic policy response to preference erosion: from trade as aid to aid for trade’.</li>

</ul>
<p>Overall the papers highlight the importance of the EU preferential arrangements to LDCs and certain other developing countries (notably the ACP), with the EU accounting for 40% of ‘Quad’ trade preferences for developing countries. The papers also highlight the fact that while at the aggregate level for all developing countries the losses from preference erosion are outweighed by the trade gains of multilateral liberalisation, ‘for a limited number of preference-dependent countries, deep global reforms will have significant costs’. However the spread of reciprocal free-trade agreements is also eroding the value of preferences. Furthermore, in the agricultural sector the process of internal EU reform is greatly reducing the impact of any multilateral agreement on the overall significance of preference erosion. The papers highlight the importance of preferences to LDCs and conversely the concentration of losses from preference erosion in a number of island economies dependent on a limited range of products, notably sugar and bananas. </p><p>In terms of the policy response the papers advocate: </p>
<ul>

<li>addressing the negotiating priorities of preference-dependent countries in other areas of the WTO negotiations, rather than holding back the process of multilateral trade liberalisation;</li>

<li>the adoption of certain trade-based solutions , such as improving rules of origin, so as to enhance the use of preferences in ways which offset the economic impact of preference erosion;</li>

<li>the implementation of new preferential market-access arrangements by non-OECD importers;</li>

<li>‘aid for trade’ to help countries to adjust, and to exploit remaining and emerging trade opportunities.</li>

</ul>
<p>It calls for any such mitigation measures to be ‘closely targeted at the countries at risk’.</p><p>The publication on distortions to agricultural incentives in Africa includes chapters on Madagascar, Mozambique, South Africa, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Ethiopia, Kenya, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda, Cameroon, Côte d’Ivoire, Ghana, Nigeria, Senegal, Benin, Burkina Faso, Chad, Mali and Togo. The overview paper argues that the poor record of poverty reduction in Africa is attributable to the agricultural policy choices made which have had an anti-agricultural anti-trade bias. A switch to less-biased policies is held to be a relatively recent one. The paper maintains that ‘agricultural price, trade and exchange-rate policies have reduced the earnings of African farmers quite substantially’. In the post independence period in the agricultural sector ‘the average rate of taxation … rose sharply’, with the 1980s beginning to see significant reductions in this anti-agricultural bias in Ghana, Uganda, Tanzania, Cameroon, Senegal and Madagascar. In Kenya and Mozambique a pro-farmer policy emerged, while an anti-agriculture bias remained in Côte d’Ivoire, Zimbabwe and Zambia up to 2004. However, it noted considerable variation across products with basic foodstuffs such as sugar rice and milk receiving assistance, while tropical export crops such as coffee, cocoa, cotton and tobacco were more heavily taxed. Most of the taxes imposed take the form of trade taxes.</p><p>While the bias against agriculture is being reduced, growth in the sector means that ‘the total value of annual transfers from farmers has risen’ (threefold for Africa as a whole). However, overall ‘there has been substantial reform towards less distortion of incentives’, although ‘there are still many opportunities for policy change that would be both pro-poor and pro-growth, raising income for low income farmers and improving resource allocation within and between countries’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
