				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>These publications provide the wider context to many of the underlying policy debates taking place around the development of EU-ACP agricultural trade relations, and as such provide essential background reading for situating current policy discussions at the ACP-EU level. With regard to the publication on preference erosion, a common feature of the analysis is the relative neglect of any substantial assessment of the process of erosion of the value of ACP trade preferences arising from the initiation of the EU domestic-reform process in the agriculture sector. These internal reforms serve to lay the foundations for subsequent bilateral and multilateral trade liberalisation beyond the ACP/LDC group. Outside of the banana sector, it is this first phase of erosion of the value of traditional ACP trade preferences which has had the greatest impact on the ACP agricultural trade position with the EU, not the subsequent process of erosion of the margins of preference at the multilateral level.</p><p>In looking at options for responding to the process of erosion of the value of preferences the analysis also neglects the growing product differentiation on EU markets (which has increasing commercial significance as the process of reform is approaching completion) and the scope for serving ‘luxury purchase’ components of this market, as part of the response to the erosion of the value of preferences. This represents one area where highly targeted support could prove extremely valuable in assisting ACP exporters in maintaining a profitable presence in the EU market in the context of both the erosion of the value of ACP trade preferences and their margins of tariff preference.</p>
		</div>
		
